begin_memory_text: Where we lived and what we did for work
middle_memory_text: The band Bright Eyes and Conor Oberst
rest_of_day_open: Well it's the weekend and I do not have to work so I think it will be going very well. I am going to see the fall leaves in the mountains and I will teach a yoga class and go to the farmers market. I am really excited to relax and enjoy my time.
critical_positive: We had a good amount in common career wise and interest wise. We were able to talk about where we both lived, my interest in Texas, our careers in academia, and a shared common interest in a band. We both also were friendly and let the conversation flow easily. I think we both gave a good effort.
critical_negative: I don't think anything did not work. We had a really good conversation and it was easy to talk to my conversation partner. We both allowed the other to finish their sentence if we accidentally interrupted and we stuck to talking about commonalities. It was an easy and enjoyable conversation.

begin_memory_text: We talked about where we lived and where we worked. She told me about her job and where she was planning to work in the near future. We talked a little bit about Texas since I live there and she was born in Fort Worth.
middle_memory_text: She mentioned that she might move to Houston in a couple years for work. My wife is from Houston so I told her what I thought about it. We discussed the cost of living in Houston versus Washington D.C.
end_memory_text: I talked about the classes that I'm teaching this semester. She talked about her work in a grant funded program having to do with AIDS research. She told me about the current status of the treatment of AIDS and how that plays into her work.
rest_of_day_open: I have a lot of work to do this weekend, but I'm looking forward to it anyway. I didn't finish everything I need to do, so I will spend a good deal of time on it. Still, I'm in good spirits about the rest of the week because I get to sleep in and spend time with my family.
critical_positive: We had a lot in common. She and I both work at universities. We have common interests in music. Also, we're both involved in grant-funded work. This gave us many avenues of conversation to explore. In fact so many, that I could have continued to talk with her for another 30 minutes easily.
critical_negative: I'm not much of a story teller, so often my answers to people's questions are a bit short and don't have a satisfying conclusion. So she would tell interesting stories and I would kind of just lay out the facts. Also, during the end of the conversation I was having a hard time following some of the details about her work.
